Therefore, in a resource-aware setting, it is more appropriate to consider
 probability measures that map events to a finite set of elements computable
 with a fixed set of resources
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Artstein1972,PuriRalescu1983"

\end_inset

.
 The simplest such set, and the one we will consider exclusively in this
 paper, is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{2}=\left\{ \imposs,\poss\right\} $
\end_inset

 together with the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\vee y=\imposs$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y=\imposs$
\end_inset

.
 In relation to the first definition, one can interpret 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
imposs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

as the closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,0]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
poss
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

as the half-open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vee$
\end_inset

 as the addition of intervals.
 The definition of a probability measure in this case is modified as being
 a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\Omega)=\poss$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for a collection 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

, of pairwise disjoint events, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\bigcup_{i}E_{i})=\bigvee_{i}\pmeas(E_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

