\begin_layout Standard
If we consider set with more values, the probability measure may give us
 more information about the coins.
 For example, despite 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\poss$
\end_inset

, we may also adopt three more values: 
\begin_inset Formula $\unlikely$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

as the interval
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,\frac{1}{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\likely$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

as the interval
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overflow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

